Ba'athist Triumvirs: Everybody Go Home! [1]

That's the order that echoed through the streets at the fever-pitch
demonstrations at noon on September 10, 1951 in the streets of Cairo,
Alexandria, and throughout Egypt. The failure of a succession of
governments, brawls and encounters with British troops, and a
disastrous King's Government led General Mohammed Naguib to deliver
the following message to the King on the night of September 9:

&quot;In view of what the country has suffered in the recent past, the
complete vacuity prevailing in all corners as a result of your bad
behavior, your toying with the constitution, and your disdain for the
wants of the people, no one rests assured of life, livelihood, and
honor. Egypt's reputation among the peoples of the world has been
debased as a result of your excesses in these areas to the extent that
traitors and bribe-takers find protection beneath your shadow in
addition to security, excessive wealth, and many extravagances at the
expense of the hungry and impoverished people. You manifested this
during and after the Palestine War in the corrupt arms scandals and
your open interference in the courts to try to falsify the facts of
the case, thus shaking faith in justice. Therefore, the army,
representing the power of the people, has empowered me to demand that
Your Majesty abdicate the throne to His Highness Crown Prince Emir
Ahmed Fuad, provided that this is accomplished at the fixed time of 12
o'clock noon tomorrow, and that you depart the country before 6
o'clock in the evening of the same day. The army places upon Your
Majesty the burden of everything that may result from your failure to
abdicate according to the wishes of the people.&quot;

Perhaps underwhelmingly, the King readily abdicated in favor of his
son, Fuad II. [2] Farouq then slipped out of the Summer Palace in
Alexandria to Cyprus, and thence, Malta, and into a longstanding exile
in the Cotswolds.

The Officers' Council for Arab Rebirth, having gained a majority of
the Officers' Board, established control of major traffic circles and
squares in Cairo, while Ba'athist cadets captured the Citadel, and Air
Force officers hand over the airfields. For a coup, it is smooth as
silk, and nearly bloodless. For more detail, see Laila Abu Lughod's
landmark study: &quot;A Velvet Revolution: Ba'athism on the Nile.&quot;

Amid gunsmoke and fires, Col. Rustum, General Naguib, and others
debated the form of the new national government. While some argued for
the deposition Fuad II and creation a 'Restored Arab Republic of
Egypt' or a 'Free Socialist Republic of Egypt' in line with sleek,
modernist thinking, they did not succeed. Instead, the will and charm
of Col. Ahmed Rustum prevailed and the monarchy survived-perhaps
because King Fuad II has shown such great affection for the Arab hero,
though Rustum believed at the time that while the monarchy was corrupt
and 'a rotten instrument of the British King,' he also believed that
the people of Egypt were not yet 'dialectically prepared for a 'total'
or 'complete' revolution' which would bring them to a rebirth, and
thus a period of revolutionary transition is required, though no such
statement was made publicly at the time.

Contemporaneously, all political parties were encouraged to apply for
licenses, registering the names and residences of their leadership and
top members. While the Muslim Brotherhood, the Communist Party of
Egypt, Wafd, and the newly-minted Ba'athist Party registered at,
elections were then suspended for at least three years. During that
time, Mohammed Naguib to served as Prime Minister, Naguib as Deputy MP
and Interior Minister, and both served on a tripartite panel with
Naguib and Badawi to try 'autocrats, kleptocrats, and enemies of the
Arab people'-essentially the ancien regime, though Fuad II served as a
figurehead and a rubber stamp, he was able to intervene occasionally.
Fundamentally, that meant the liquidation and expulsion of only the
worst pro-British collaborators, save those who agree to stay and
serve to 'profitable in the service of the interests of the Egyptian
people and the Arab Nation.' Such that only a tiny amount of capital
flight went abroad.

Likewise, Rustum's Greco-Italian wife, who converted and took the name
Khadija, takes prominence as a sort of 'first lady' of Egypt as the
King is unmarried, and serves to reassure the Coptic, Greek, Armenian,
Italian, and Jewish communities. Though her husband's cold
technocratic fascism was yet to reveal itself in full, it was
certainly felt throughout the country.

The emergence of the Naguib government helped push Clement Atlee out
of office by October 1, while the Truman Administration drifted,
concentrating on Korea and Iran-a third world crisis only served to
frustrate and irritate Dean Acheson. Czechoslovakia and the PRC were
relatively warm to the Naguib government, and the USSR tentatively
extended congratulations on 'revolution' based on the rhetoric of the
new regime. In all cases, Rustum treaded lightly, attempting to tack
between the West and the Communist Bloc, knowing full well which side
the Egyptians are mad at, which side might supply economic/military
aid, and which side he needs to supply cash to build the Aswan High
Dam.

All of this was marked with pomp and parades hardly out of step with a
California Farmer's Harvest Festival, despite a prominence of goose-
stepping and jackboots-the resplendent military parades carry a strong
whiff of May Day in the USSR, as does the idea of the Ba'athist
International, which met in Cairo in April 1952.

In retrospect, it was a landmark moment, a veritable who's who of
early Ba'athism. At the time, the pomp and circumstance at the Citadel
far outranged the number of attendants, or their collective-the
prominence. As King Fuad II looked on from his apartments, Rustum and
Prime Minister Naguib addressed the assembled Ba'athists from under
the French clock, broken since its donation in the 1840's.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;From Syria came Wahib al-Ghanim, Michel Aflaq, Antun Maqdisi, Akram al-
">

Hawrani, Salah al-Din al-Bitar, who represented the Ba'athist-Arab
Socialist high command in Syria. [3] In addition, three military
officers attend the conference Col. Adnan al-Maliki and his fanboys,
Mustafa Tlass and Hafiz al-Assad. In other words, one martyr and two
future Presidents of the Ba'athist Republic of Syria.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;From Lebanon, the Gayamel Clan, masters of the fascist Kataeb Party-
">

descended by way of Spanish Falangism-attend alongside the Jumblatts,
representing the Progressive Socialist Alliance as well as the Druze,
whose mutual enmity declined and whose alliance is sometimes dated
from this era.

The contingents from Iraq, Yemen, and Jordan were less than notable at
this time. Iraq was in the waning days of its monarchy, while Yemen
was still a colony, and Jordan's Ba'athist Party was years away from
being established.

Nonetheless, everyone went home happy, save the Syrians, who faced
three more years of tumult before taking power.

For Rustum, the conference was a success. While the Syrians held the
lead as theoreticans of Ba'athism, he was able to have himself elected
Secretary General of the Ba'athist International, the popular heart,
if not the brain or soul, of Ba'athism. After that, his second
invitation to Anthony Eden regarding the Suez Canal was accepted, a
date set for November 1952....

Thoughts?

[1] Mad trivia points for anyone who gets this.

[2] OTL, Fuad was born last of Farouq's children, and was three years
old in 1952. In the ATL, Fuad was his firstborn. As a male teenager,
he shifts attitudes toward the monarchy, and with a serious fascist
fetish, he is easier to keep up, despite the tumbledown reputation of
the monarchy. Whether this will endure, well....

[3] Al-Hawrani briefly established an Arab Socialist Party in Syria in
1952; the Ba'athists joined it, and soon overtook it in OTL. Here,
they accept the invite.
