To put it simply &quot;it depends. &quot;It depends on how the Israeli Supreme
Court has read it (IMO the Israeli SCC has done a good job with these
things, and there are many. YMMV). I also depends on how you view the
Israeli political parties, since every other party will essentially
imply their opponents violate all 3 (if you think American attack ads
are nasty, Israeli attack ads are far nastier).

I think the change, (ironically enough) was to ban the Kahanists. More
ironically parties on the right that are allowed to sit  (i.e. they
are cleaned up heirs of Kahane) and which probably violate (2) and (3)
(I'm thinking largely of the secular nationalists to the right of
Likud) like to crow that the various Arab parties violate (1) and
should be banned. The Arab parties have probably complained about
their opponents on the right. But all of them are in the Knesset.

ITTL things are rather different. AFAIK Israeli Arab politics were,
from what it looks, all about patronage and &quot;cooperation&quot; (patronage)
in the 50s and 60s, coupled by the fact that some rather egregious
violations on Arab citizens civil rights ensured things did not get
out of hand (all could vote, but their civil liberties were quite
restricted; curfews, police surveillance, movement restrictions etc.).
All the restrictions were lifted in 1966, however (why then, I'm not
sure; I do know there was a gradual shift away from restrictions over
time, starting in cities, and then ending in the 60s with lifting of
restrictions in majority Arab areas), but the emergence of wholly Arab
focused parties did not really emerge until the mid 1970s and later
and today radical (and perfectly moderate) Arab politics are an
important factor. I suppose the mobilization lag is because while
living in Israel created Arab communities that discarded older
patronage centric approaches to politics, old habits die hard. I
should note something similar happened with Jews of North African and
Middle Eastern descent too--they began as tied to Labour and then over
time left. Still I have never seen numbers on the effect of the Arab
vote. It's unlikely to be decisive in the 1950s and 60s (I think the
proportion of the population that is Arab-Israeli has increased over
time) due to the factors I've noted. That being said, I understand
Arab voters &quot;staying home&quot; was seen as what cost Shimon Peres his
chance for PM after Rabin's assassination. Certainly when I was in
Israel in 2000 there were lots of Labour Party posters in Acre, for
instance, which has a large Arab community. Where the Arab vote sits
now is complex (given the wackiness of Israeli politics, or if you
prefer, the emergence of a centerist coalition), but again in the ATL
in the 1950s I have no doubt the Arab community leadership was
accomodationist, and those in Israel seem unlikely to stray just yet.
It probably helped that the less cooperative leadership were those who
actively resisted the emergence of the State and as such were highly
likely to have vacated or were vacated (note that I have no wish to
spark an ugly discussion on population shifts, forcible or otherwise
in 1948-49). Those most likely to incline towards revolution would be
in Jordan, in Syria, in Lebanon, or in Gaza.

If my view is broadly correct the accomodationists are unlikely to be
swept away by &quot;successful&quot; Baath in Israel, at least not yet, though
it may lead to some marginally increased radicalization.

I do think, however, the Israeli courts would be more pliant in the
1950s and 1960s. Israel, AFAIK, has always had a fairly vigorous
judiciary, but I doubt they would be nearly as bold as the Israeli
courts have been in the last decade or so. In particular the
increasing shift by the court to &quot;constitutionalize&quot; the Basic Law.
